{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a6a9ecac-047f-4411-9b91-fd9839916848","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **abstract file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Use `System.IO.Abstractions`** (NuGet package) — it provides `IFileSystem` wrapping `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, etc., plus a `MockFileSystem` for tests.\n\n2. **Or roll your own** minimal interface:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileService\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\n3. **Inject it** via constructor DI, replacing direct `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls.\n\n4. **In tests**, use `MockFileSystem` (from the package) or a simple mock/stub of your interface.\n\n`System.IO.Abstractions` is the community standard and saves you from maintaining your own wrapper. Install with:\n\n```\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\nWant me to refactor your project to use this pattern?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7a35d55-e1c9-4f17-a307-d592fe2d6a81","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a software design question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide advice based on common patterns.\n\nThe standard approach is to use the `System.IO.Abstractions` library or create your own file system abstraction interface. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":362,"requestId":"BD18:AF6EC:1ECF693:22A2AFB:6A07CAB1"},"id":"173b89a9-643c-4b88-8355-15c3bd5d23be","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:39:06.990Z","parentId":"7a3ec3d9-ffc8-41fa-86f4-62bee66f6208"}
